THE QUIET ACRE

A found-footage investigation horror short.
Worked example for the screenplay-creation skill — demonstrates the
Step 2 structural blueprint, Step 3 formatting conventions, Step 4 cast
conventions, and Step 5 escalation toolkit end to end. Fully original:
new title, characters, setting, and mythology.

====================================================================

FRAMING CARD

THE FOLLOWING FOOTAGE WAS RECOVERED FROM A CAMERA BAG FOUND IN A
PARKED VEHICLE OFF FORESTRY ROAD 9, HALLOW PINE FOREST, ON OCTOBER 4.

IT HAS BEEN COMPILED IN THE ORDER IT WAS SHOT.

TWO OF THE THREE PEOPLE WHO APPEAR IN IT HAVE NOT BEEN FOUND.

====================================================================

COLD OPEN

INT. FOREST - NIGHT (HANDHELD, DENNY'S CAMERA) [TIMESTAMP 10/03 23:47]

Frame is chaos: branches, a flashlight beam swinging wild, breathing
loud and close to the mic.

DENNY (O.S.)
Ivy. IVY. Say something if that's you, say something that ISN'T—

A beat of pure black. Just breathing.

Then, very quiet, very close — a voice, flat, almost sing-song:

VOICE (O.S.)
...six...

The camera drops. Lens pointed at leaf litter, one boot in frame,
unmoving.

Static.

TITLE CARD

THE QUIET ACRE

====================================================================

ACT ONE — NORMALCY AND SETUP

INT. MARA'S APARTMENT - DAY (WEBCAM / SCREEN RECORDING) [10/01]

MARA VOSS, 30s, host of a small true-crime documentary series,
talks directly to camera. Behind her: a corkboard, red string,
photocopied newspaper clippings.

MARA
Okay — so if you've watched the channel before, you know I don't
usually do disappearances I can't close. This one, I don't think
I'm going to close. I'm doing it anyway.

She taps the corkboard. A grainy 1987 photo of five teenagers.

MARA (CONT'D)
October 1987. Five kids go into Hallow Pine Forest outside Corwith
Falls for a weekend camping trip. Four days later, a search party
finds one backpack, one boot, and a cassette tape wedged in the fork
of a tree eleven feet up. No bodies. Ever.

SCREEN INSERT — LOCAL NEWS CLIP, OCT 1987, TIMESTAMPED IN CORNER

Grainy anchor desk. Chyron: "CORWITH FALLS TEENS STILL MISSING."

ANCHOR (ON SCREEN)
...search efforts have been scaled back after twelve days, with
authorities citing the size and difficulty of the terrain known
locally as the Quiet Acre...

MARA (V.O., OVER FOOTAGE)
"The Quiet Acre." That's a name locals use for a stretch of the
forest that — and I want to be careful how I say this — doesn't
show up consistently on any survey map. Not "hard to map." Not
consistently the same shape twice.

INT. MARA'S APARTMENT - DAY (WEBCAM) [10/01, CONT'D]

DENNY RUIZ, 30s, sits across from her, arms crossed, a laptop open.
He's the crew's audio/tech person and resident skeptic.

DENNY
For the record, I think "doesn't show up consistently on maps" means
"forestry service redrew a boundary in 1994" and not "haunted."

MARA
Noted for the record.

She turns to a third chair, currently empty.

MARA (CONT'D)
Ivy's meeting us Thursday. She didn't want to be on camera until
we're actually there.

INT. CAR - DAY (HANDHELD, DENNY'S CAMERA) [10/03, EN ROUTE]

IVY LINDQVIST, late 20s, sits in the back seat, a photograph in her
lap — one of the five 1987 teens, a girl who looks like a younger
version of her.

IVY
That's my aunt Cheryl. She was seventeen. My mom was twelve when it
happened, spent the rest of her life driving past the turnoff to
Forestry Road 9 without looking at it.

DENNY (O.S.)
You don't have to do the on-camera stuff if it's —

IVY
I want to know what happened to her. I don't care whose camera that
is.

INT. DINER - DAY (HANDHELD) [10/03]

RETIRED DEPUTY HOLT WEEMS, 70s, a coffee going cold in front of him.
Local witness. He's told this story before and clearly wishes he
hadn't been found again.

WEEMS
I was on the search in '87. Six days in, dogs wouldn't go past a
certain line of trees. Not spooked — just sat down. Refused. Never
seen that before or since, and I've run dogs in that forest thirty
years.

MARA
What's the "counting" thing? We found references in old case notes.

WEEMS
(long pause)
Tape recorder they found in the tree. Had eleven minutes of one of
the kids counting. Just numbers, over and over, getting quieter.
Never got past sixty. We don't play that tape for people anymore.

SCREEN INSERT — CASSETTE TRANSCRIPT (TYPED CASE FILE, SCANNED)

"...forty-one...forty-two...forty-three..."
[MARGIN NOTE, HANDWRITTEN: recorder found running, batteries should
have died 3 days prior per manufacturer spec — unconfirmed]

WEEMS (CONT'D)
Rule locals still tell their kids, if you're ever back in there:
don't answer if something says your name twice. First time might be
a person. Second time's never a person.

====================================================================

ACT TWO — DESCENT

EXT. FORESTRY ROAD 9 - DAY (HANDHELD) [10/03, 14:12]

The crew parks at a rusted gate. Mara holds a photocopy of the
original 1987 search grid map next to her phone's GPS.

MARA
Okay, phone says we're four hundred meters from the treeline. Map
says six hundred. That's... within margin of error, probably.

DENNY
"Probably."

They start walking.

EXT. FOREST TRAIL - DAY (HANDHELD) [10/03, 15:30]

Established trail markers, orange tape on trees, mundane hiking
footage. Ivy narrates location names from her aunt's old journal.

IVY
Cheryl's journal says they camped near "the fork," which — helpful,
there's like nine forks. But she drew a symbol next to it.

SCREEN INSERT — JOURNAL PAGE (PHOTOGRAPHED, HANDWRITTEN, 1987)

A crude spiral with three short lines radiating off one side.

DENNY (O.S.)
That's just a doodle, right? Kids doodle.

IVY (O.S.)
Sure.

EXT. FOREST - DAY (HANDHELD) [10/03, 16:50]

Denny's audio recorder, running for ambient sound, is checked on
playback. Under birdsong, faint and rhythmic, almost buried:

RECORDER PLAYBACK (V.O., DISTORTED)
...twelve...thirteen...fourteen...

DENNY
(staring at the recorder)
Okay. That's — I want to say that's a bird. I don't actually think
that's a bird.

MARA
Keep it running.

EXT. FOREST CLEARING - DUSK (HANDHELD) [10/03, 18:05]

They find a tree with the spiral symbol from Ivy's journal carved
into the bark — old carving, but the cuts look clean, unweathered,
wrong for something forty years old.

IVY
(touching the bark)
This shouldn't still be sharp.

Mara's compass app spins freely, no fixed heading. Denny's phone
signal bar flickers to full strength, then to none, in the same
frame.

MARA
We lost the light faster than the app said we would.

DENNY
By like ninety minutes.

A long pause. The three of them, close together in frame for the
last time in the footage.

IVY
I want to go a little further. The journal marks something past
this tree.

DENNY
It's getting dark, Ivy —

IVY
Twenty minutes.

Mara looks at Denny. A decision neither of them says out loud.

MARA
Denny, hang back here, see if you can get one bar and call it in so
someone knows the grid ref. Ivy and I go twenty minutes, we turn
around whether we find anything or not.

DENNY
(not happy, but not stopping her)
Twenty minutes.

They split. This is the last footage in which all three appear.

====================================================================

ACT THREE — CRISIS

EXT. FOREST - NIGHT (HANDHELD, DENNY'S CAMERA) [10/03, 19:40]

Denny alone, phone held up searching for signal, flashlight in his
other hand. His breathing is the loudest thing in the mix.

DENNY
(to camera, low)
No bars. No bars anywhere. I'm gonna — I said twenty minutes, it's
been thirty-five, I'm going after them.

He starts walking. The counting is audible again, closer now, not
coming from the recorder — from the treeline.

VOICE (O.S., DISTANT)
...fifty-eight...fifty-nine...

DENNY
(to camera)
That is not Ivy's voice. That is not Mara's voice.

He walks faster. This is where COLD OPEN footage begins — the
chaotic branch-and-flashlight sequence, the dropped camera, the
single close word: "...six..."

EXT. FOREST - NIGHT (AUDIO ONLY, RECOVERED FROM MARA'S PHONE)
[TIMESTAMP CORRUPTED — ESTIMATED 10/03, LATE]

Black frame throughout. Two voices.

MARA (O.S.)
—said your name, Ivy, did it say your name—

IVY (O.S.)
(very calm, too calm)
It said it twice.

MARA (O.S.)
Ivy. Ivy, look at me. Don't answer it. Don't answer it a third—

The audio cuts. Not fades — cuts, mid-syllable.

Forty-one seconds of silence.

Then, once, very close to the phone's mic, a voice that sounds
almost like Mara's own, badly imitated:

VOICE (O.S.)
...eighty...

Silence. End of recovered audio.

====================================================================

EPILOGUE

TEXT CARD

DENNY RUIZ'S CAMERA WAS RECOVERED 40 METERS FROM THE PARKED VEHICLE.
THE FOOTAGE ABOVE IS EVERYTHING IT CONTAINED.

TEXT CARD

MARA VOSS'S PHONE WAS RECOVERED INTACT, FULLY CHARGED, INSIDE THE
LOCKED VEHICLE. NEITHER SHE NOR HER PHONE HAD BEEN THERE WHEN THE
VEHICLE WAS FIRST SEARCHED, ELEVEN HOURS EARLIER.

TEXT CARD

NO TRACE OF IVY LINDQVIST HAS BEEN FOUND.

TEXT CARD

A SEARCH VOLUNTEER LOGGED A HANDHELD RECORDER FOUND RESTING ON TOP
OF A TRAIL MARKER, BATTERIES FRESH, SERIAL NUMBER CONSISTENT WITH A
MODEL DISCONTINUED IN 1989. IT WAS NOT PLAYED.

TEXT CARD

THIS FOOTAGE IS PUBLISHED WITH THE LINDQVIST FAMILY'S PERMISSION.

FADE OUT.

END.
